1 Introduction

The following analysis is on presidential election data from 2000 to 2020. This data will be used to create two subsets, one of county-level winners. This data set keeps the person that had the most candidate votes each year, in other words, keeping the winner and their party for each county each year. This data will be plotted in a Tableau interactive choropleth map.

2 Data Management

Import data

election<-read.csv(url("https://melaniemiller1.github.io/STA533/w09-HW/PresidentialElection2000To2020.csv"))
  1. County-level Data (1). Calculate the percentage of each participating party within each county. (2). Keep only the winning party in the data set
county.level<-election %>%
  group_by(county_name, year) %>%
  filter(candidatevotes == max(candidatevotes, na.rm=TRUE))
county.level <- county.level %>%
                      mutate(party.pct = (candidatevotes/totalvotes)*100)


write_csv(county.level, file = "C:/Users/mille/Documents/WCU Grad School 2022-2024/WCU Grad Spring 2024/STA 533 Data Visualization/STA533/w09-HW/county_level.csv")

To achieve this, I decided to filter the election data by the county name, as well as year and only keeping the candidate that had the maximum votes (aka the winner) for each year.

  1. State-level Data (1). Calculate the percentage of each participating party within each state. (2). Keep only the winning party in the data set
state.level<-election %>%
  group_by(state, year) %>%
  filter(candidatevotes == max(candidatevotes, na.rm=TRUE))
state.level <- state.level %>%
                      mutate(party.pct = (candidatevotes/totalvotes)*100)

write_csv(state.level, file = "C:/Users/mille/Documents/WCU Grad School 2022-2024/WCU Grad Spring 2024/STA 533 Data Visualization/STA533/w09-HW/state_level.csv")

To achieve this, I decided to filter the election data by the state, as well as year and only keeping the candidate that had the maximum votes (aka the winner) for each year.

3 County Level Presidential Election

This map shows the presidential election results by county in the United States.This map can look at each year individually or all years with the filter, and the counties are colored by party. The states in the center of the US tend to be more Republican while places like the east coast tend to be more Democrat.

4 State Level Presidential Election

This map showes the presidential election party winners by state. This map can be filtered by year to see any differences per state, and each state is colored by the party of the winner. As the years go on, it appears more states turn Democratic. In comparison to the county level, this gives a more broad look at similar data. In the county level map, it appeared that there was much more red on the map, however in the state level, it appears that there is more blue. County populations obviously differ so though the county level appears to have more red, blue populations may be greater in some counties - making the state blue.
